text:
Why is it so easy to drain an Ethereum wallet? Users can pre-approve future token transfers. 

#Cardano does not have an approval mechanism, so users' wallets are more protected.

Ideally, a smart contract should not have an owner or any mechanism that permits the owner to transfer assets from the smart contract to an external address.

This attribute endows smart contracts with a degree of trust.

Users can confidently delegate their assets to a smart contract (trust the code, not people), secure in the knowledge that no third party can manipulate these assets.

Nonetheless, it is possible to incorporate a transfer function into the #Ethereum smart contract, which enables the owner to transfer tokens from the smart contract to another address.

Ethereum drainers contain a ‚ÄòtransferFrom‚Äô function that is used to move tokens from the user‚Äôs wallet to the smart contract.

Then a ‚Äòtransfer‚Äô function is used to transfer tokens to the attacker's address.

See Figure 1.

When interacting with a smart contract, users often have to approve the contract to spend a certain amount of tokens from their wallet. 

This is known as a 'token approval' transaction.

Normally, for non-malicious use cases, this is useful. 

For example, users can approve a DApp to buy assets at a target price without moving assets out of the wallet in advance.

The transfer is to happen at the appropriate time.

Once the 'approve' transaction is signed, the smart contract can call the 'transferFrom' function at any time without requiring any further approvals or actions from the user.

The 'transferFrom' function is an on-chain transaction and requires GAS fees, which are paid from the user‚Äôs wallet automatically.

Both the 'approve' and 'transferFrom' transactions require GAS fees.

In both the Cardano and Ethereum ecosystems, there‚Äôs a risk that an attacker might trick you into signing a transaction that transfers more assets than you intended.

Unlike Ethereum, Cardano‚Äôs smart contracts don‚Äôt have an equivalent approval mechanism.

Cardano's smart contract can‚Äôt be granted unlimited access to a user‚Äôs wallet. 

A malicious smart contract can‚Äôt drain a user‚Äôs wallet without the user explicitly signing a transaction for each transfer.

Cardano uses the UTxO model where assets are stored in unspent outputs rather than as balances in accounts.

In this model, a transaction has inputs and outputs, where the inputs are unspent outputs from previous transactions.

Each UTxO can only be consumed once and as a whole. 

Therefore, there‚Äôs no equivalent to Ethereum‚Äôs approve function in Cardano‚Äôs UTxO model.

Typically, a transaction only involves a limited number of UTxOs that a user possesses in their wallet.

Any UTxOs that are not included as inputs in the transaction remain unaffected by the transaction signature.

From a security point of view, this model can be seen as more resistant to drain wallet attacks.

See Figure 2.

Alice has to sign every single transaction that spends UTxO. It is not possible for a smart contract to arbitrarily transfer UTxOs owned by Alice.

An Ethereum account, represented by a single address, can hold balances of multiple different types of tokens, including various ERC-20 tokens.

The approve function doesn‚Äôt usually grant spending approval for the whole account. 

Instead, it grants a specific smart contract the approval to spend a certain amount of a specific ERC-20 token from the user‚Äôs account.

However, malicious smart contracts can be unintentionally approved to spend tokens from the user‚Äôs entire account.

Ethereum users are used to providing approval.

The approval mechanism can be exploited by malicious smart contracts to drain tokens from a user‚Äôs wallet without requiring any further approvals or actions from the user.

See Figure 3.

Alice only signed the ‚Äòapprove‚Äô transaction. This allowed the malicious smart contract to transfer all tokens from her account. The wallet gets drained.

To prevent the loss of all assets from their account, users should ensure that they only grant spending approvals to trustworthy smart contracts.

Ethereum‚Äôs approve function provides developers with a feature akin to permitting a third party to periodically withdraw a specified amount from your bank account.

While this is a useful function, it requires users to trust the third party not to exceed their withdrawal limit.

Cardano does not offer a similar feature to developers. Users are required to explicitly sign each transaction that spends UTxOs from their wallet.

Both approaches have their merits.

The respective teams had to strike a balance between ensuring security and providing a wide range of options for developers when crafting smart contracts.

While Cardano‚Äôs scripts are designed to verify if the conditions for spending UTxOs have been met, Ethereum‚Äôs smart contracts can gain control over user accounts.

text:
The treasury is an underrated strength of Cardano.

Currently, the #Cardano treasury holds 1.5B $ADA, equivalent to approximately $930M. 

It‚Äôs plausible that this could soon reach a valuation of $5B.

This substantial budget can facilitate remarkable achievements over a well-structured protocol.

Every epoch, ADA coins are added to the treasury, constituting 20% of the epoch‚Äôs reward budget. 

This reward budget comprises fees and 0.3% of coins from the reserve.

Presently, ADA coins for Catalyst are sourced from the treasury.

With the introduction of on-chain governance, ADA holders will make decisions about the treasury. 

They will set the project‚Äôs priorities, fully utilizing the wisdom of the crowd.

Many projects ended after the ICO fever due to budget exhaustion.

Many L1s are children of VC funds. They exist solely to make money. The team might be largely driven by what VC funds dictate.

The dependence of a blockchain project on VC funds is an unwanted phenomenon and centralizes the project from a management perspective to a large extent.

Cardano is not threatened by the imminent exhaustion of the budget for maintenance and innovation of the protocol. Nor is there a threat of takeover by VC funds.

Thanks to the treasury, the decision-making power remains in the hands of ADA holders.

It‚Äôs astounding to see the multitude of impressive projects that have emerged on Cardano, regardless of whether they received Catalyst funding.

With the backing of ADA coins from the treasury, these initiatives can experience a substantial boost in development speed and parallelization.

With the backing of its treasury, Cardano has become an unstoppable force.

quote.text:
@CryptoHayes posted a interesting article to his substack highlighting how filecoin is an obvious play for the next bullrun. I'd like to use his reasoning to highlight why I believe @IagonOfficial $IAG is a superior option and has the potential to be a game changer on #Cardano.

He states that the growing AI business sector will need cloud computing and storage. Demand is rising. üíΩ üìÇ

"Because I have no clue as to which AI business models will succeed, I want to invest in the things I know AI will rely on to function ‚Äì i.e., its¬† food groups. Either I need to invest in compute power in some way, or I need to invest in cloud data storage. For both food groups, an AI craves decentralisation. An AI faces existential risks if human-controlled, centralised companies decide to restrict access to their services (due to coercion by governments, for example).

A cryptocurrency powered blockchain enabling humans to come together and share spare compute power would be interesting, but I haven‚Äôt identified a coin or token with a network that is built out enough to suggest it will survive and thrive over the next two to three years. So, as far as I can tell, there‚Äôs no decentralised way for me to invest in compute power.

That leaves me with investing in data storage."

"This is why I don‚Äôt want to own the stock of a large cloud data service provider like Amazon. I fundamentally believe what Amazon is ‚Äì¬† a large, centralised company governed by human laws ‚Äì is not compatible with what an AI needs from its data hosting provider. Amazon could, at the behest of a government, unilaterally shut off access to data. That is not possible in a censorship-resistant decentralised network. I know that, due to their consensus mechanisms and economic rewards, blockchains can help create coordinated ‚Äúsharing‚Äù. That is why the decentralised data storage network powered by FIL is a must have for the burgeoning AI economy". 

This is where we get to @IagonOfficial. Unlike filecoin, $IAG is regulatory compliant, which is key for onboarding businesses. Not only that but it will have a superior user experience. ‚úÖ

But you'll note that filecoin does not have computational resources as part of it's platform, something Hayes, a well studied investor, did not find a viable option for. Iagon will likely be the first protocall in all of crypto to have both in one single user friendly, regulatory/data compliant, but decentralized package!

Think about it. An easy one stop shop for decentralized storage and computational resources all in one easy, regulatory compliant friendly,  package-in-a-box. And it's home is on #Cardano. The future is bullish. The potential for $IAG is massive. Let's all contribute our resources and turn this into the best decentralized resource provider in the industry. üí™

You can read the full article here: 
https://t.co/hCZszBuADJ

text:
#Cardano uses a variation of the Nakamoto consensus called Ouroboros.

It is a Proof-of-Stake consensus that uses the underlying principles invented by Satoshi Nakamoto for #Bitcoin.

Ouroboros is designed to provide similar security guarantees as PoW while being more energy-efficient.

Let's look at the Nakamoto consensus from the perspective of safety and liveness. Then I will explain how it affects the finality of transactions.

Safety and liveness are two critical properties that ensure the network operates correctly and securely.

Teams building network consensus must balance these properties. They have to decide which one they prefer more.

Safety refers to the guarantee that the network will not reach a false agreement. 

It ensures that any transaction deemed final by one properly-operating node will eventually be deemed final by every properly-operating node.

It also means that no two transactions ever deemed final by two properly-operating nodes will ever conflict.

In the extreme case, this can be interpreted as the network preferring stopping the consensus to the incorrect settlement of transactions.

In a network that prioritizes safety over liveness, avoiding forks of blockchain is crucial because a fork implies that there is a disagreement on the state of the ledger, which can lead to safety violations.

For #Solana, #Ripple, and others, blockchain forks are unwanted events that can slow down transaction processing or even shut down the network.

Discarding transactions is highly undesirable for such a network because it might undermine the trust and reliability of the system.

Users expect their transactions to be final and immutable once they are included in a block and the block is appended to the blockchain.

These networks have the advantage of having fast transaction finality.

You can see this undesirable situation in Figure 1.

The network created two N+4 blocks, and there are different transactions in each of the blocks (small red and blue boxes). The network must discard one of the N+4 blocks including all transactions.

These are different requirements from networks that prefer liveness over safety.

Liveness is the guarantee that the network will continue to make progress and not stall. 

As long as there are transactions that have not been finalized, the set of finalized transactions will continue to grow.

It ensures that every transaction will eventually be settled by all honest nodes.

A network that prioritizes liveness over security doesn't stop when it forks.

Instead, it allows two chains to exist temporarily and relies on network participants to continue building on top of the chain they believe is the correct one.

An inconsistent state of the ledger is temporarily tolerated.

In Figure 2, you see a similar situation as in Figure 1.

The lower block N+4 is discarded (including the red transaction). A block N+5 is added into which the red transaction was inserted. Both sets of transactions are ultimately in the blockchain. The network has not stopped.

I hope you know which property prefers a network using the Nakamoto consensus.

Cardano and Bitcoin both prioritize liveliness over safety.

In Nakamoto consensus, nodes are instructed to follow the longest chain when a fork occurs.

This rule ensures that the network continues to make progress and extend the blockchain, even if there are temporary disagreements or forks.

The network will eventually converge on one of these blocks (chains) as part of the longest chain rule, but until then, there could be conflicting views of the transaction history.

The safety property is eventually restored as the consensus continues in adding new blocks. One chain becomes significantly longer than the others, making it the universally accepted chain.

Safety and liveness properties are related to the probabilistic finality of the Nakamoto consensus.

Probabilistic finality refers to the concept that the finality of a transaction is not absolute at the time it is inserted into a new block.

The finality of a transaction becomes increasingly likely as more blocks are appended on top of the block containing the transaction.

Safety and liveness relate to probabilistic finality in the following way:

Safety means that once a transaction has been included in a block and several blocks have been added on top of it (deepening its position in the chain), the likelihood of that transaction being reversed becomes very low.

However, it‚Äôs not zero.

There‚Äôs always a small chance that a longer competing chain could emerge, although the probability decreases exponentially with each additional block.

Liveness ensures that transactions will eventually be confirmed and added to the blockchain. 

Transactions are not guaranteed to be included in the next block (for example, the network might be clogged), but they will be included eventually as long as they are valid and the network continues to operate.

Compared to other network consensus that prefer safety over liveness, the Nakamoto consensus has a slow settlement.

The user has to wait for the network to append several blocks on top of the block in which his transaction was inserted.

Every other newly added block (on top of the block with the user‚Äôs transaction) represents an agreement with the state of the ledger.

Figure 3 shows that Alice's transaction (small blue box) was inserted into block N+3.

The finality of the transaction is 0, as no further block has been added yet. With each additional block appended, the finality of the transaction (and also of the block N+3) increases. Once the N+4 block is appended, the finality is 1, and so on.

If Alice needs 3 blocks as a sufficient number of confirmations, she can consider the transaction finalized (irreversible) in block N+6.

Networks preferring safety over liveness can finalize transactions more quickly. 

That is, not through appending blocks, but through some form of voting either before or shortly after creating a new block.

This kind of consensus usually requires a large number of nodes to actively participate in voting on each block. 

Have a look at the #Ethereum consensus.

The finality of transactions can be quickly achieved only if it is possible to obtain the approval of a new state (block) from the required amount (%) of nodes in a short time.

If a large number of nodes suddenly become unavailable, safety-preferring networks may not be able to continue producing blocks while liveness-preferring networks can (but usually more slowly).

text:
According to Messari's State of Cardano Q4 2023, we are growing in all relevant stats.

When you take other reports from Messari and compare #Cardano with projects like #Ethereum, #Avalanche, #Algorand, and others, you realize that we have to work on adoption.

See the Table.

Avalanche, Ripple (XRP Ledger), Algorand, and Ethereum lead in the number of daily transactions.

#Bitcoin, Ethereum, and #Solana lead in the number of active daily addresses.

In TVL, Ethereum, Solana, and Avalanche lead.

It stands to reason that older ecosystems have a larger user base. 

Cardano is still a young platform. The DeFi ecosystem is in its infancy, but it is developing dramatically.

The next bull run will be the first in which Cardano will have a DeFi ecosystem. I expect the number of users to increase.

In terms of the number of users, all ecosystems are roughly similar - they have several tens of thousands of users. 

Only Ethereum has roughly a 10x lead. With Solana, it may (or may not) be fake data.

The number of transactions is very high for some projects, especially Avalanche and Algorand. In the context of the number of users, they are far too high.

It is possible that in some use cases, a small number of users send a large number of transactions to each other.

It doesn't make sense with Solana, as each user would have to make an average of about 200 transactions per day.

It is possible that Messari does not distinguish between successful and failed transactions.

Some ecosystems are ahead of Cardano, but not too far. 

Cardano needs new users and significant partnerships.

USD-backed stablecoin would also help a lot. 70% of transactions on blockchains concern stables.

text:
Plutus V3 is a massive upgrade that will bring new possibilities for applications built on #Cardano.

V3 includes advanced primitives and tools that give developers more options for writing smart contracts (scripts).

Teams focused mainly on performance, throughput, size of SC, and new capabilities.

Last year, Valintine's upgrade supported ECDSA and Schnorr, allowing interoperability with #Bitcoin.

V3 adds new cryptographic primitives that allow building sidechain bridges and increase interoperability with other blockchains.

Probably the most expected is the support of the Zero-Knowledge proofs (ZKP) system.

ZK cryptography will allow developers to build ZK rollups and ZK smart contracts.

This will enable communication between #Midnight and Cardano.

Midnight is a partner chain of the chain of Cardano.

Cardano will be capable of similar things to Midnight to some extent. 

Midnight is built from the ground up with a focus on privacy, so it will always be ahead of the curve.

The @ENCOINS1 team has announced that we are several months away from ZK smart contracts on Cardano.

Plutus language contains built-in functions that are commonly used in scripts. V3 brings new functions.

For example, 17 new primitives that support cryptographic curves. It opens doors to seamless sidechain implementation and integration with Mithril.

Furthermore, a cryptographic hash function Keccak-256 which produces a 256-bit hash value.

It is commonly used for secure data verification on #Ethereum. Supporting it in Plutus will allow for building cross-chain solutions and support a few community projects.

V3 introduces bitwise primitives that allow developers to manipulate bits at a low level. This will have a positive impact on higher performance.

For example, developers will have a primitive allowing highly efficient conversion between Integers and Strings.

CIP-58 adds a class of low-level functions for highly efficient algorithms and data structures. 

It adds the ability to build efficient hash tables, a common key-value mapping data structure, etc.

A common way of encoding data types in Plutus Core is by using the Scott approach. This approach is inefficient.

Plutus V3 introduces Sums of Products (SOPs). 

This is a new way of encoding data types that leads to smaller and cheaper scripts compared to Scott encoding.

The Vasil hard-fork, deployed in September 2022, brought Plutus V2.

V2 had a significant impact on the efficiency of smart contracts.

V3 again brings higher efficiency, but also new possibilities.

Plutus V3 is available for testing on SanchoNet.

text:
Staking $ETH on Ethereum may require a banking license in Switzerland while staking $ADA on Cardano does not.

The difference is in custodial vs. non-custodial staking.

#Cardano's liquid staking seems a more suitable solution not only for decentralization but also from the point of view of regulations.

What is liquid staking?

‚û°Ô∏è Cardano does not define a minimum number of coins that users need for staking. They therefore do not need to look for a third party that would stake coins from multiple users.

‚û°Ô∏è Cardano has no lockup periods. ADA coins can be spent at any time during staking.

‚û°Ô∏è Cardano doesn't have slashing. Users may not receive rewards if the pool misses opportunities to mint blocks. They will never lose their ADA if they keep them in their own wallet.

‚û°Ô∏è Delegating ADA coins to a pool is very easy. It only requires a few clicks in the wallet (it can be a light wallet). You can then close the wallet.

Some regulators seem to distinguish between direct staking and staking through a third party. 

They also distinguish whether the coins can be spent at any time or whether the system requires locking and slashing.

When staking through a third party, users must send coins, such as ETH, to a custodian. A custodian is a central entity that is responsible for users' coins. 

Users usually get "liquid tokens" that have the same price as coins but that have no role in the consensus. 

If the custodian carries out staking on its own account, crypto assets cannot be segregated in the event of bankruptcy and trigger capital requirements for banks.

Why does #Ethereum require custodians?

‚û°Ô∏è To run the validator, you need to own 32 ETH (~85K USD).

‚û°Ô∏è If users have less ETH, they usually look for a third party. These are either centralized exchanges or projects like Lido. These entities represent counter-party risk.

‚û°Ô∏è Ethereum has slashing (can confiscate staked coins) and therefore it is necessary to lock ETH. Users cannot spend staked ETH immediately.

‚û°Ô∏è Running a validator from home requires technical knowledge, a reliable internet connection, and an uninterrupted power source.

This type of regulation in Switzerland is similar to the SEC crackdown on exchanges in the US.

The problem is that if CEX, for example, goes bankrupt, ETH can be confiscated to pay debts to creditors.

It appears that third-party staking will be regulated in many countries.

It is surprising how well regulators understand the details of PoS consensus and decentralization.

Cardano is more decentralized than Ethereum due to liquid staking.

Vitalik indirectly admitted that he likes liquid staking on Cardano and that his project should go in the same direction. It's time to do it.

Source: https://t.co/38ZOBtn28L

quote.text:
Hey @RichardMcCrackn our favorite Ethereum killer app is @circle USDC! $27B marketCap and drives majority of trading volume and DeFi activity across all chains as the most widely adopted and regulated fiat stablecoin in existence.

Oh wait it‚Äôs 2024 and Cardano still doesn‚Äôt support native USDC forcing users who want access to the most trusted stablecoin to incur bridge risk or use one of the 15-20 other chains it‚Äôs natively available on. It‚Äôs a basic integration every smart contract chain with real developer and user adoption must have, to argue otherwise is to blindly ignore the data.

Have you listened to the latest @IOHK_Charles interview with @cryptorecruitr? A @Cardano_CF led discussion with Circle dating back to 2021 has not materialized into anything meanwhile multiple foundations for other L1s a fraction the size of Cardano have launched native USDC support on mainnet.

Skip to Charle‚Äôs USDC points starting at 37:30: https://t.co/RIT4xI8nKJ

Almost feels like we may have the wrong set of people leading these discussions if after this long there‚Äôs been no tangible progress. This is not what advocating for the best interest of Cardano adoption and growth looks like at all.

For all the talk about ‚ÄúRealFi‚Äù and having a meaningful positive impact on economic activity in the real world this is honestly a sad and embarrassing current state for the Cardano ecosystem. This is not about decentralization or Intersect or Voltaire or other stablecoins on Cardano. This is about giving Cardano users the option to choose the stablecoin they prefer and empowering developers to build more competitive products by tapping into USDCs global liquidity layer as the most widely adopted and trusted stablecoin ever created.

If you have read up until this point it must mean you care about the future growth and adoption of Cardano the same way we do, for this we say thank you. More importantly though if you do care please take this as a public call to action for the community to demand better from @Cardano_CF and @InputOutputHK to get USDC integration completed. The best time to hold the founding entities more accountable for completing a task most other foundations complete in a few months timeline was in 2021 when the CF led discussions with Circle started, the 2nd best time is now.

quote.text:
I'm fully aware of BitVM. We did some of the foundational research with EUTXO and also Plutus. Team orange doesn't seem to get that a ton of Cardano's infrastructure is a direct conceptual successor to ideas started by Bitcoin like Color Coins and utxo based smart contracts. 

The issue is getting value into the L2 and out, the security model, the latency of settlement, and many other functional requirements for practical DeFi. It works until it doesn't and you need something from Bitcoin. Bitcoin doesn't give it so you give up and federate to a multisig at the end of your design. Then you pretend that is somehow decentralized and is ok. It's not.
